,"meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Indian Ashit, Indu, Naina, Partha, Soumya, Ajit, Anjan, Anjana, Anup, Arjun, Arun, Ashim.","English, Scottish, and Welsh: variant of   Day  .","German: topographic name from a field name in North Rhine-Westphalia, denoting a sizeable piece of land, from Middle Low German <i>dē</i> ‘thigh’ (referring to the shape of the property)."]}]},{"name":"Berles","type":"LAST","attribution":"Dictionary of American Family Names © Patrick Hanks 2003, 2006.","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  Spanish Alvaro, Jose, Carlos, Cesar, Florina, Gustavo, Luis, Margarita, Mariana, Mercedes, Ramon, Xavier.","German (Lower Rhine): topographic name for someone who lived on a hill, from a shortened form of   Berghaus  . Compare   Berkes  .","French (<b>Bergès</b>): Gascon variant of <b>Vergès</b> (see   Verges  )."],"variants":[{"name":"Berghaus","meanings":["German: topographic name denoting a house on a hill, a compound of <i>Berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’ + <i>Haus</i> ‘house’. Compare   Berges  ."]},{"name":"Berkes","meanings":["Some characteristic forenames:  German Kurt, Otto.","North German: topographic name for someone who lived on a hill, shortened from <i>Berg-hūs</i> (<i>Berg</i> ‘mountain, hill’ + Low German <i>hūs</i> ‘house’). It is a variant of <b>Berkus</b> or   Berges  .","Hungarian: from a pet form of the personal names <i>Bernát</i> or <i>Bertalan</i>, Hungarian forms of   Bernard   and   Bartholomew  , respectively."]}]},{"name":"Isabelle","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["form of   Isabel  , now in frequent use in the English-speaking world."],"variants":[{"name":"Isabel","meanings":["Originally a Spanish version of   Elizabeth  , which was coined by deletion of the first syllable and alteration of the final consonant sound to one that can normally end a word in Spanish. The name was imported into France in the early Middle Ages, and thence into England. It was a royal name, and its enduring popularity may have been enhanced by the fact that it was borne by a queen of England—  Isabella  (  1296–1358 ), daughter of  Philip IV  of France—even though she led a turbulent life and eventually had her husband,  Edward II , murdered."]}]}],"lifeSummary":"When Isabelle De Berles was born about 1180, in Berles-au-Bois, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France, her mother, Marie de Boisleux, was 19 and her father, Wallerland de BERLES, was 28. She had at least 2 sons with Gauthier De Hebuturne II. She died about 1238, in Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France, at the age of 60."},"et":{"about 1180–about 1238":"umbes 1180–umbes 1238","1164–1221":"1164–1221","1197–1259":"1197–1259","1200–Male":"1200–Surnud","1162–1214":"1162–1214","1153–1217":"1153–1217","1180–1238":"1180–1238","about 1180":"umbes 1180","1197":"1197","1153":"1153","1164":"1164","1162":"1162","1180":"1180","1217":"1217","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1214":"1214","1200":"1200","1178":"1178","about 1238":"umbes 1238","1221":"1221","about 1221":"umbes 1221","Hamelincourt, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Hamelincourt, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Berles-au-Bois, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Berles-au-Bois, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa","Hébuterne, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Hébuterne, Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, France":"Pas-de-Calais, Hauts-de-France, Prantsusmaa","Hébuterne, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, France":"Hébuterne, Pas-de-Calais, Nord-Pas-de-Calais, Prantsusmaa"},"fi":{"about 1180–about 1238":"noin 1180–noin 1238","1164–1221":"1164–1221","1197–1259":"1197–1259","1200–Male":"1200–Kuollut","1162–1214":"1162–1214","1153–1217":"1153–1217","1180–1238":"1180–1238","about 1180":"noin 1180","1197":"1197","1153":"1153","1164":"1164","1162":"1162","1180":"1180","1217":"1217","1238":"1238","1259":"1259","1214":"1214","120